children.text:
Congratulations! You're 12 weeks pregnant and you are almost done your first trimester. 

Your body continues changing and now you may have increased pigmentation. As a result, you can get “mask of pregnancy” or chloasma. 

Main tips for this week: take brisk walks, eat high-fiber foods, drink plenty of water to help keep your intestinal tract moving. Walking for 15 - 60 minutes each day will be really good for your body and baby. Your breasts may hurt, try a new sports bra, or even two sports bras for super support.

You may notice changes in your skin: darkening of the areolas, irregular dark patches on face and neck. Don't panic! It is chloasma (the mask of pregnancy). It will disappear after delivery, or at least become lighter.

The next weeks will be a period of rapid growth for you and the baby. As you produce more blood and amniotic fluid, you may feel desperately thirsty. Just drink plenty of water or milk and forget carbonated drinks. So it will be a good idea to carry a drink with you to keep your fluid levels up.

At this week, your baby is about the size of a lime. You child will have a recognizable appearance. The eyes will move closer together. The ears will move closer to their final position. The fingers, toes and eye muscles will start to move. 

The intestine will grow very fast. Currently, it is actually an extension of the umbilical cord, but it will begin to move back into the abdomen in the near future. The kidneys can secrete urine, and the nervous system is continuing to mature. 

The good news is that your baby may have developed complex reflexes such as sucking.

Your baby's heart works really well and you already can hear it. For pregnant women, obstetricians and midwives use a familiar medical device known as a Doppler fetal heart monitor to detect the fetal heart rate. This is a standard practice during regular consultations, and one which pregnant mothers look forward to. 

You might be surprised to know that you can readily purchase a Doppler fetal monitor for your own convenience. Though it may not be advisable for use before 12 weeks of gestation, as the fetal position may make it challenging to locate the heartbeat. 

To successfully pick up your baby’s heartbeat, choose a Doppler fetal monitor with a frequency of at least 3 MHz and position the transducer just right above the pelvic bone. The normal fetal heartbeat is at 120-160 beats per minutes. It may take some practice to locate the heartbeat, but there is no mistaking in that fast, galloping sound.
